data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages. Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count)` or `Assert.IsTrue(users.Any())` | Clearer intent |
| `Assert.IsTrue(count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Better failure message |

**Other `CollectionAssert` helpers:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);  // same items, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);       // same items, same order
```

The main principle: use the most specific assertion available — you get meaningful failure messages like `"Expected: 3. Actual: 1"` instead of `"Assert.IsTrue failed"`.
